The point, though, is not just censorship, but its inverse: propaganda. Tik=
Tok=E2=80=99s algorithm, unmoored from the constraints of your social netwo=
rk or professional content creators, is free to promote whatever videos it =
likes, without anyone knowing the difference. TikTok could promote a partic=
ular candidate or a particular issue in a particular geography, without any=
one =E2=80=94 except perhaps the candidate, now indebted to a Chinese compa=
ny =E2=80=94 knowing. You may be skeptical this might happen, but again, Ch=
ina has already demonstrated a willingness to censor speech on a platform b=
anned in China; how much of a leap is it to think that a Party committed to=
 ideological dominance will forever leave a route directly into the hearts =
and minds of millions of Americans untouched?

Again, this is where it is worth taking China seriously: the Party has show=
n through its actions, particularly building and maintaining the Great Fire=
wall at tremendous expense, that it believes in the power of information an=
d ideas. Countless speeches ( https://palladiummag.com/2020/07/08/the-theor=
y-of-history-that-guides-xi-jinping/ ) , from Chairman Xi and others, have =
stated that the Party believes it is in an ideological war with liberalism =
generally and the U.S. specifically. If we are to give China=E2=80=99s lead=
ers the respect of believing what they say, instead of projecting our own b=
eliefs for no reason other than our own solipsism, how can we take that cha=
nce?

